"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 4–8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-4-8.py

Ch 4: Battle of Aphek; ark captured; Hophni and Phinehas die; Eli dies; Ichabod born.
Ch 5: Ark among the Philistines; Dagon prostrated; plague spreads through Philistine cities.
Ch 6: Ark returned; guilt offerings; Beth-shemesh incident; Kiriath-jearim receives the ark.
Ch 7: Samuel's reform at Mizpah; Philistine defeat; Ebenezer memorial stone.
Ch 8: Samuel's corrupt sons; demand for a king; royal administration warning.

Context focus: archaeology of Philistine cities, ANE ark/deity theology, Mizpah archaeology,
plague evidence, geopolitics of the Philistine pentapolis, ANE kingship institution.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(type_, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(type_, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

CONTEXT = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The battle of Aphek (modern Tell Ras el-ʿAin near the Yarkon springs) was one of the most strategically significant engagements of the Iron Age I period. Aphek controlled the northern coastal plain where the main north-south trunk road descended from the Carmel pass — whoever held Aphek could control movement between Egypt and Syria. The Philistines chose the ideal terrain for their chariots and iron weapons. This was not a border skirmish but a decisive confrontation for dominance of the central highlands.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Israel's initial defeat of about four thousand men was severe but not catastrophic. The elders' assessment — 'Why has YHWH struck us down today before the Philistines?' — reflects the standard ANE assumption that military defeat indicates the anger of the patron deity. The question they ask is the right theological question; the solution they devise (fetching the ark) is the wrong theological answer. Bringing the divine object to the battlefield was practiced throughout the ancient Near East — Egyptian armies carried statues of gods; Assyrian armies brought cult images. Israel's elders are reaching for an ANE common solution.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The ark of the covenant — the gold-overlaid acacia wood box housing the stone tablets, topped by the two golden cherubim — was both Israel's most sacred cult object and the footstool/throne-base of the invisible YHWH. The design mirrors the thrones of ANE deities, whose statues sat on or between cherubim-like figures. To bring the ark to battle was to bring YHWH's throne into the field — the ultimate escalation. Shiloh, where the ark was housed (in a permanent sanctuary, <em>bêt YHWH</em>), was approximately 40 km from Aphek.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Hophni and Phinehas carry the ark into the Israelite camp. The shout that goes up — so great the earth resounds — is the battle cry of a people now confident that their divine patron is physically present. The detail that Hophni and Phinehas accompany the ark underscores the irony: the very priests whose corruption made YHWH's judgment inevitable are now the custodians of his most sacred object. Their presence with the ark is not protection but exposure.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Philistines hear the great shout from Israel's camp and ask each other what it means. When they learn the ark of YHWH has come into the camp, they are afraid — 'God has come into their camp!' The Philistine fear acknowledges YHWH's power while misunderstanding its operation. Their subsequent military resolve ('be strong and act like men') is the pragmatic response of soldiers who fight anyway despite recognizing the odds. Their fear proves justified theologically but wrong militarily: the ark's presence does not protect Israel.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Philistines know the reputation of YHWH's previous acts in Egypt — 'these are the gods who struck Egypt with every kind of plague in the wilderness.' Their historical knowledge of the Exodus plagues is a remarkable detail: the Philistines, who arrived in Canaan from the Aegean around 1200 BCE, were aware of the Exodus tradition (presumably through Canaanite oral history and perhaps Egyptian records of the events). The plural 'gods' reflects their polytheistic framework applied to YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Philistine call — 'Be strong and act like men, or you will be slaves to the Hebrews as they have been to you' — is the rallying cry of soldiers facing a reversal of the existing power dynamic. The word 'Hebrews' (<em>ʿiḇrîm</em>) is used here in its socially loaded sense — the term outsiders used for Israelites, often with implications of lower status. The Philistines are fighting to maintain the social hierarchy that has given them dominance since the destruction of the Late Bronze Age city-states.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Philistine officers acknowledge the formidable reputation of YHWH — 'Who can deliver us from the hand of these mighty gods?' — but still call their men to fight. This reflects a realistic Iron Age military calculus: even against a more powerful opponent, a disciplined professional force can defeat a numerically superior but undisciplined levy. The Philistines' military professionalism, iron weapons technology, and chariot forces gave them structural advantages over the Israelite tribal levy.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Philistine battle cry 'Fight like men!' is addressed specifically to themselves — a self-exhortation against the terror the ark's arrival produced. The fear acknowledged and then overcome is the military psychology of professional soldiers who have learned to operate despite fear. The Philistines' ability to regroup after the initial panic is part of what makes them so formidable throughout this period.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Philistine victory was catastrophic: thirty thousand Israelite foot soldiers killed, the ark captured, and Hophni and Phinehas dead. The contrast with the four thousand of the first battle indicates a rout of the entire army. Archaeological evidence from Shiloh shows destruction layers consistent with a major assault around this period — the sanctuary city appears to have been destroyed (though the narrative does not describe this directly; Jeremiah 7:12 references the destruction of Shiloh as historical memory).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The ark of God is captured and Eli's two sons die in the same verse. The narrative's compression is deliberate: the two judgments fall simultaneously — the priestly line ends and the covenant symbol departs at the same moment. The fulfillment of the man of God's oracle (2:31-34) is total and immediate. That the prediction specified both sons dying on the same day (2:34) is confirmed by this single verse's double report.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A Benjaminite runner arrives at Shiloh with his clothes torn and dust on his head — the standard ANE markers of mourning and defeat. The torn garment in particular was the universal disaster signal in the ancient Near East; both Egyptian and Mesopotamian texts describe messengers arriving with torn clothing to signal catastrophic news. The reader already knows the news from vv10-11; the narrative now shows how it reaches those waiting at Shiloh.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Eli is sitting on a seat beside the road watching for news of the ark — not merely waiting passively. His concern is specifically for the ark, not for his sons. This detail is the narrative's last redemptive observation about Eli: whatever his failures as a father and administrator, his primary anxiety is for the covenant symbol rather than for his family. The road he watches is the road from Aphek, along which the messenger is now running.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The city cries out when they hear the news. The collective mourning of Shiloh — the city that had housed the ark throughout the period of the judges — anticipates the archaeological destruction. Shiloh was Israel's central sanctuary from the conquest (Josh 18:1) through the beginning of the monarchy. Its loss as a functioning center was the end of an era; the ark would not return to a fixed sanctuary until Solomon's temple.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Eli is 98 years old and his eyes are fixed — the same condition attributed to him earlier (3:2, <em>ʿênāyw qāmû</em>, his eyes had grown dim). The blindness is both physical and symbolic: the high priest who failed to see what his sons were doing, who required a child prophet to deliver YHWH's word to him, now waits in literal darkness for news of the object he can no longer see.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The messenger identifies himself as 'one who has come from the battle line today.' In ANE military contexts, battlefield survivors carrying reports held a specific social status — they were witnesses whose firsthand testimony was authoritative. Eli asks: 'How did the matter turn out, my son?' The address 'my son' is the elderly judge's habitual courtesy.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The messenger's report delivers the news in escalating severity: (1) Israel fled before the Philistines, (2) there was a great slaughter, (3) your two sons Hophni and Phinehas are dead, (4) the ark of God has been captured. The sequence leads from military disaster to personal loss to theological catastrophe. The narrative knows that the fourth item — the ark's capture — is the most devastating, and the messenger delivers it last.</p>",
    "18": "<p>When the messenger mentions the ark, Eli falls backward off his seat at the side of the gate — his neck breaks and he dies, 'for the man was old and heavy.' The grim physical detail ('heavy') is the narrative's unsentimental closing note on Eli's administration. The gate was the judicial seat of authority; Eli's fall from his judicial seat is literalized as a fall from his seat of governance. He had judged Israel for 40 years — the standard generation-length of a major period.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Phinehas's wife, pregnant and near term, hears the news of the ark's capture, her father-in-law's death, and her husband's death simultaneously. Labor begins immediately — the confluence of three catastrophic shocks bringing on premature delivery. The woman is unnamed throughout; her identity is entirely constituted by her relationships to the men who have all just died.</p>",
    "20": "<p>As she was dying, the women attending her say: 'Do not be afraid, for you have born a son.' The birth announcement formula — 'a son is born to you' — was the prescribed formula for delivering good news in the ancient world; a male heir was the primary social insurance for a widow. But the dying woman does not respond to comfort or to the news of a son. Her grief is theological, not personal.</p>",
    "21": "<p>She names the child Ichabod (<em>ʾîḵāḇôḏ</em>) — 'Where is the glory?' or 'The glory has departed/gone into exile.' <em>Kāḇôḏ</em> (glory) is YHWH's visible, radiant presence — the divine weightiness that fills the sanctuary and makes it holy. Her naming-speech: 'The glory has been exiled from Israel (<em>gālāh kāḇôḏ miyyiśrāʾēl</em>) because the ark of God has been captured.' The name records Israel's theological condition with brutal concision. The Shekinah theology that runs through the entire Hebrew Bible begins with this exile.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'The glory has been exiled from Israel, for the ark of God has been captured.' This is the dying woman's last word and the chapter's theological epitaph. The identification of YHWH's glory with the ark's presence — and its departure with the ark's capture — is the basis for the entire ark narrative of chs 5-7. The narrative raises a question it does not immediately answer: can YHWH's glory be permanently exiled, or will it return?</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The Philistines take the captured ark from Ebenezer (near Aphek) to Ashdod, one of the five cities of the Philistine pentapolis. Ashdod is on the coastal plain approximately 50 km southwest of Aphek — a significant transport distance for a heavy acacia wood and gold object. Placing a captured enemy's cult object in your own temple was standard ANE victory theology: the capture of a deity's image or cult object demonstrated that your god had defeated their god. Ashdod would have been the ideal site — home of Dagon's primary sanctuary.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Philistines place the ark in the temple of Dagon, setting it up beside the Dagon statue. Dagon was a major Semitic grain deity (<em>dāgān</em> = grain) widely worshipped across Syria-Palestine — not exclusively Philistine. The Philistines adopted Dagon from the Semitic population they conquered. Archaeological excavations at Ashdod have uncovered fragments of what may be a Dagon cult image, consistent with a significant temple complex. Placing Israel's ark beside Dagon expressed the Philistine theological claim: YHWH is now Dagon's subordinate, a trophy of Dagon's superior power.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The next morning the Ashdodites find Dagon fallen face down before the ark of YHWH. They set him up again — the practical response of a temple staff discovering a toppled cult image. The narrative does not explain the mechanism; the night-fall of the statue is presented as a fact requiring no elaboration. The detail that Dagon is face down (<em>ʿal pānāyw</em>) before the ark is the ANE gesture of complete submission — a defeated vassal prostrated before a conqueror.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The second morning: Dagon is again fallen face down before the ark, but now his head and both his hands have been cut off and lie on the threshold, with only his torso (<em>dāgôn</em>) remaining. The decapitation and severing of hands are the treatment of a defeated enemy in ANE warfare — Assyrian reliefs routinely show scribes counting severed hands of the defeated. The torso labeled <em>dāgôn</em> may be a wordplay on the deity's name and the word for fish (<em>dāg</em>), or simply the term for the body trunk. The threshold becomes a sacred disgrace-site.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The narrative preserves a cultic etiology: the priests of Dagon and all who enter Dagon's temple at Ashdod do not step on the threshold to this day. Threshold taboos were widespread in ANE religion — thresholds were liminal spaces associated with divine or demonic presence. This specific taboo marks where Dagon's defeat was made permanent by the severed hands and head. The verse is the narrator's note that this cultic custom was still observed in his own time.</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH's hand weighs heavily on the Ashdodites, ravaging them with tumors (<em>ʿŏpālîm</em>). The word <em>ʿŏpālîm</em> in the MT denotes swellings or tumors; later scribal tradition marked it as a <em>qere</em> (oral reading substitute) for the written <em>ṭĕḥōrîm</em>. The affliction spread across the district. Modern scholars have noted that the LXX adds details about mice, and the later golden guilt-offering (6:4-5) includes both mice and tumors — suggesting the disease may have been bubonic plague, transmitted by rats/mice and manifesting in swollen lymph nodes (buboes). The geographical spread along trade routes is consistent with this.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The people of Ashdod recognize the causal connection: 'The ark of the God of Israel must not remain with us, for his hand is harsh against us and against Dagon our god.' The acknowledgment is both practical and theological — YHWH's hand is described as affecting their deity as well as their people. The Philistine lords (<em>sĕrānîm</em>) are consulted — the five Philistine lords governed their cities with a collective authority structure that was distinctive in the region. 'Lord' (<em>sārēn</em>) may be related to Greek <em>tyrannos</em>.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Philistine lords confer: what should they do with the ark of Israel's God? The decision to move it to Gath is the political compromise of a committee — rather than returning it, they transfer the problem to another city. Gath (Tell es-Safi) was approximately 25 km east-northeast of Ashdod, also in the Philistine heartland. The same affliction follows the ark to Gath, killing a great number there too.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The same affliction strikes Gath: 'the hand of YHWH was against the city, causing a very great panic, and he struck the men of the city, both young and old, so that tumors broke out on them.' The expansion of the plague to Gath, following the ark's transfer, establishes the pattern: the ark's presence is the cause, not the specific location. YHWH's 'hand' (<em>yaḏ YHWH</em>) is the active metaphor — the divine fist pressing down on each Philistine city in sequence.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The ark is sent to Ekron (Khirbet el-Muqanna, recently identified with more certainty at Tel Miqne). The Ekronites immediately object: 'They have brought the ark of the God of Israel to us to kill us and our people.' The third city already knows what happened at Ashdod and Gath; the ark's reputation has traveled faster than the cart. The cry of Ekron was 'a deadly confusion throughout the whole city' — the entire city mobilizes in protest before the ark even settles.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Philistine lords assemble at Ekron: 'Send the ark of the God of Israel back to its place, that it may not kill us and our people.' The death toll at Ekron is described as 'very great' and 'the hand of God was very heavy there.' The verb used for the dying is <em>hammaṯ</em> (were dying), implying an ongoing process rather than a single event — consistent with disease rather than instant divine judgment. The panic is total.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Those who did not die were struck with tumors, and the cry of the city went up to heaven. The phrase 'cry went up to heaven' (<em>shawaʿaṯ hāʿîr ʿālāh haššāmayim</em>) echoes the outcry that reaches YHWH in Genesis 4:10 (Abel's blood) and 18:21 (Sodom's cry). The Philistines' distress, though they are not covenant people, still rises to YHWH. The ark narrative operates within a theology of universal divine sovereignty, not merely a tribal covenant claim.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The ark remained in Philistine territory for seven months — a specific temporal detail that anchors the narrative in historical memory. Seven months is long enough for the full scope of the plague to develop and the political will to return the ark to solidify. The Philistine lords consulted their own religious specialists: priests and diviners (<em>kōhănîm wəqōsəmîm</em>). The ANE pattern of consulting technical religious experts for plague-management decisions is well-documented in Hittite and Mesopotamian sources.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Philistine priests and diviners are asked: how shall we send back the ark? They insist it must not be sent back empty — it must be accompanied by a guilt offering (<em>ʾāšām</em>). The <em>ʾāšām</em> is the specific reparations-payment for desecration of the sacred in Israel's cultic law (Lev 5-6). The Philistine religious experts are recommending a protocol that aligns closely with Israelite sacral law — whether through direct knowledge of Israelite practice or through the common ANE understanding that sacred objects require proper propitiation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The advice: 'If you send back the ark of the God of Israel, do not send it empty, but by all means return to him a guilt offering. Then you will be healed, and it will be known to you why his hand does not turn from you.' The logic is diagnostic: send the guilt offering not merely as appeasement but as a test — if healing follows, the connection between the ark and the plague is confirmed. This is proto-empirical reasoning applied to a theological question.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Five golden tumors (<em>ʿŏpālê zāhāḇ</em>) and five golden mice (<em>ʿakḇārê zāhāḇ</em>) — one per Philistine lord and city. The five cities of the Philistine pentapolis were Ashdod, Gath, Ekron, Ashkelon, and Gaza. The golden replicas of the plague symptoms — tumors and mice — follow ANE sympathetic magic practice: a golden image of the affliction offered to the deity is a way of returning the affliction to its divine source. The mice add the disease-vector detail that supports the bubonic plague identification.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Make images of your tumors and images of your mice that are ravaging the land, and give glory to the God of Israel. Perhaps he will lighten his hand from you and from your gods and from your land.' 'Give glory' (<em>nəḵaḇḇēḏ</em>) — the verb from <em>kāḇôḏ</em> — is the proper response to YHWH's weight pressing on them. The Philistines are advised to do in action (giving glory through the guilt-offering) what Eli's sons refused to do in worship (1 Sam 2:29-30: 'those who honor me I will honor').</p>",
    "6": "<p>The priests rhetorically invoke Pharaoh: 'Why should you harden your hearts as the Egyptians and Pharaoh hardened their hearts? After he had dealt severely with them, did they not send the people away, and they departed?' The comparison to Pharaoh is striking — the Philistines' own religious specialists counsel against the resistance to YHWH that destroyed Egypt. The Exodus tradition functions here as a warning to the Philistines from within their own religious counsel.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The test prescribed: a new cart (<em>ʿăgālāh ḥăḏāšāh</em>) and two nursing cows (<em>pārôṯ ʿālôṯ</em>) that have never been yoked, with their calves shut up at home. The use of animals that have never been yoked mirrors the red heifer requirement (Num 19:2) and Deuteronomy 21:3's heifer 'that has never been worked.' In ANE sacred-object transport, ritual purity of the conveyance was required; unused animals were the standard criterion. The calves kept home remove the natural homing instinct as an explanation if the cows head toward Beth-shemesh.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The ark is placed on the cart along with the golden guilt offerings in a box beside it. The box (<em>ʾargaz</em>) is a hapax — this specific container term appears only here. Sending the guilt offerings in a separate container alongside the ark respects the boundary between the sacred vessel and the propitiation objects. The entire arrangement is the Philistine priests' best attempt at proper sacred transport.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Philistines prescribe an observable test: 'Watch. If it goes up on the road to its own territory, toward Beth-shemesh, then it is he who has done us this great harm; but if not, then we shall know that it is not his hand that struck us — it happened to us by coincidence.' The explicit formulation of an observable criterion for distinguishing divine causation from coincidence is a remarkable epistemological moment. The Philistine priests are constructing a controlled test of their hypothesis.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Philistines do as instructed: two nursing cows on the new cart, calves shut up at home. The detail of the calves being secured is the control element — the maternal bond should pull the cows homeward, not toward a distant Israelite town. Any deviation from that natural pull would be interpretable as supernatural direction.</p>",
    "11": "<p>They put the ark of YHWH on the cart and the box with the golden mice and golden tumors. The entire guilt-offering apparatus is loaded — nothing is left behind. The Philistine priests have prepared the reparations as completely as their knowledge allows. The departure of the cart from Philistine territory is the climax of the ark narrative's first half.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The cows go straight (<em>wayyišṣarnāh</em> — the verb from <em>yāšār</em>, straight/direct) on the road to Beth-shemesh, mooing as they go, not turning to the right or to the left. The mothers' lowing (<em>wayyiggāʿagnāh</em>) as they walk away from their calves makes the supernatural direction audible: every instinct says turn back, but they go straight ahead. The Philistine lords follow behind as far as the border of Beth-shemesh — witnessing the test's outcome.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The people of Beth-shemesh are harvesting wheat in the valley when they see the ark coming — and rejoice. Beth-shemesh ('house of the sun god') was an Israelite city in the Sorek Valley, at the boundary between Israelite and Philistine territory — precisely the cultural-geographic boundary the ark crossed. The wheat harvest provides the flat threshing floor (v14) and the timing: late spring, when the agricultural calendar created public gatherings of the whole community.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The cart comes into the field of Joshua of Beth-shemesh and stops near a large stone. The Levites take down the ark of YHWH and the box of golden objects and place them on the large stone. The wood of the cart becomes firewood and the cows become a burnt offering. The large stone functions as an impromptu altar — the cart becomes its own sacrificial pyre. The spontaneous burnt offering of the transport animals is a response of gratitude without prior planning.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Levites come down from the cart — the text assumes Levites are present at Beth-shemesh, consistent with the Levitical cities distribution (Josh 21:16 includes Beth-shemesh as a Levitical city). The Levites are the proper handlers of the sacred objects; the narrative's mention of them preserves the requirement that sacred transport required qualified personnel. The men of Beth-shemesh offer burnt offerings and make sacrifices on that day.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The five Philistine lords see the events and return to Ekron that same day. Their witness-departure confirms that the test was observed by Philistine authorities. They have seen the empirical evidence — the cows went straight to Israelite territory, the ark was received by Israelites — and their theological hypothesis is confirmed. They return without further incident; the diplomatic crisis is resolved.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The golden tumors: one for Ashdod, one for Gaza, one for Ashkelon, one for Gath, one for Ekron — the full pentapolis accounted for. The specific enumeration of all five cities is the narrator's way of confirming that the guilt-offering covered the full geographic scope of the plague. Gaza and Ashkelon do not appear in the plague narrative itself but are included in the guilt-offering — either because the plague did spread there (narrative compression) or as a preventive inclusion.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The golden mice: according to the number of all the cities of the Philistines belonging to the five lords, both fortified cities and unwalled villages. The extension beyond the five city-lords to include dependent villages suggests that the plague's impact was regional, not limited to the five major urban centers. The large stone on which the ark rested became a memorial in the field of Joshua of Beth-shemesh — a specific topographical marker preserved in local memory.</p>",
    "19": "<p>YHWH struck down some of the men of Beth-shemesh because they looked into the ark of YHWH. The number in the MT is 'seventy men' (some manuscripts add 50,000, creating the impossible '50,070' of many translations — almost certainly a scribal error combining two variant readings). Seventy is the plausible number for a local incident. The transgression — looking into (<em>rāʾāh bə</em>) the ark — violates the strict prohibition on unauthorized viewing of the ark's contents (Num 4:20). Curiosity about the sacred does not constitute authorization.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The people of Beth-shemesh ask: 'Who is able to stand before YHWH, this holy God (<em>ʾĕlōhîm qādôš</em>)?' and send messengers to the inhabitants of Kiriath-jearim: 'The Philistines have returned the ark of YHWH. Come down and take it up to you.' The question — 'who is able to stand?' — is not rhetorical despair but a practical liturgical query: who has the proper cultic standing to host YHWH's ark? Beth-shemesh recognizes it cannot. The question will not be permanently answered until David's elaborate ark-procession in 2 Sam 6.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The messengers go to Kiriath-jearim — 'Kiriath of the forests,' modern Abu Ghosh or Tell el-Azhar, in the hill country of Judah near the Benjamin border. Kiriath-jearim is at the appropriate geographical and cultic distance from Beth-shemesh: far enough from Philistine territory, in the highlands rather than the valley, and accessible from the central hill country. It will house the ark for twenty years (7:2) until David's transfer to Jerusalem (2 Sam 6:2).</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The men of Kiriath-jearim bring up the ark and take it to the house of Abinadab on the hill, consecrating his son Eleazar to have charge of it. The private household custody of the ark — in Abinadab's house rather than a sanctuary — is an emergency arrangement that becomes semi-permanent. Eleazar is consecrated (<em>qiddəšû</em>) specifically for this role: the family becomes a kind of hereditary ark-guardians outside the regular Levitical structure. The ark will remain here throughout Saul's entire reign.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The ark stayed at Kiriath-jearim twenty years. All the house of Israel mourned after YHWH (<em>wayyinnāhû ḵol-bêṯ yiśrāʾēl ʾaḥărê YHWH</em>). The twenty-year gap is a generation — enough time for the Battle of Aphek generation to age significantly and for a new population to grow up knowing only the mourning condition of the ark's absence from any recognized sanctuary. The mourning after YHWH is the proper covenant response to the ark's capture, even in its return: the glory-absence created by the Shiloh disaster has not been healed by the mere physical return of the box.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Samuel's reform program requires removing the foreign gods (<em>bəʿālîm wəhāʿaštārôṯ</em> — the Baals and Ashtaroth) and directing hearts to YHWH alone. The Baals were local fertility deities of Canaanite religion whose worship Israel had persistently adopted throughout the judges period; the Ashtaroth were female fertility-deity representations. Samuel's demand for exclusive YHWH worship is the Deuteronomic covenant requirement applied after a generation of compromise.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Israelites remove the Baals and Ashtaroth and serve YHWH only. The conciseness of the reform is narrative idealization — actual religious reform in agrarian societies typically took generations. But the narrative's point is that when covenant conditions were met, YHWH delivered. The sequence of reform → assembly → confession → intercession → deliverance is the standard covenant-restoration pattern of the Deuteronomistic History.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Samuel assembles all Israel at Mizpah to intercede for them. Mizpah ('watchtower') in Benjamin — identified with Tell en-Naṣbeh, excavated extensively in the 20th century — was one of the most important assembly sites in the pre-monarchic period. The excavations at Tell en-Naṣbeh uncovered extensive Iron Age I remains consistent with a major administrative and cultic center, including a significant gate complex. Mizpah's association with covenant assemblies runs through Judges (10:17; 20-21), Samuel (7:5-16; 10:17), and the early monarchy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>At Mizpah the people draw water and pour it out before YHWH (<em>wayyiṣpəqû mayim lipnê YHWH</em>) — a ritual act not explained elsewhere in the Torah but paralleled in other ANE libation practices. The pouring out of water before a deity signified complete self-offering, possibly mourning (like the pouring out of the heart in Lam 2:19), or the dissolution of the self before YHWH. They fast and confess: 'We have sinned against YHWH.' Samuel judged Israel at Mizpah — the assembly has both cultic and judicial dimensions.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Philistines hear that Israel has assembled at Mizpah and advance against them. The large gathering at Mizpah would have been visible and audible intelligence to Philistine scouts — a national assembly was both a cultic and a military mobilization risk. The Philistines' advance at this moment puts Israel in the same strategic vulnerability as the Aphek disaster: assembled and exposed. The Israelites' fear is understandable.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Israelites cry to Samuel: 'Do not stop crying out to YHWH our God, that he may save us from the hand of the Philistines.' Their appeal to Samuel's intercession — rather than to military action — reflects the lesson of Aphek: bringing the ark (a cultic object) didn't save them; Samuel's prayer (a covenant relationship act) is the proper form of appeal. The people's request positions Samuel as prophet-intercessor whose relationship with YHWH can accomplish what military escalation could not.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Samuel takes a nursing lamb and offers it as a whole burnt offering to YHWH. He cries out to YHWH for Israel, and YHWH answers him. The 'nursing lamb' (<em>ṭaleh ḥălāḇ</em>) is young, unblemished — the highest-quality sacrifice. The combination of animal sacrifice and intercessory prayer is the proper form of covenant petition: the offering addresses the relational distance created by sin, and the prayer makes the specific request. YHWH answers — the narrative is explicit that the subsequent military events are YHWH's answer to Samuel's cry.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH thunders with a great thunder against the Philistines and throws them into confusion. The military catastrophe that follows is attributed entirely to divine action, not Israelite military capability. YHWH as warrior uses the natural world — thunder, confusion — as his weapons. This is the theophanic-war tradition of the Song of Deborah (Judg 5:20, 'the stars fought from their courses') and the crossing of the Red Sea (Exod 14:24-25). The rout at Mizpah reverses the rout at Aphek.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Israel pursues the fleeing Philistines and strikes them as far as Beth-car. Beth-car's precise location is uncertain — the name appears only here. The pursuit to Beth-car represents a significant reversal of the Aphek defeat; the Israelites are now advancing into Philistine-influenced territory rather than being driven back to their highland strongholds. The territorial implication is that the battle of Mizpah temporarily rolled back Philistine dominance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Samuel takes a stone and sets it up between Mizpah and Shen, naming it Ebenezer (<em>ʾeḇen hāʿēzer</em>) — 'stone of help.' 'Thus far YHWH has helped us' (<em>ʿaḏ-hēnnāh ʿăzārānû YHWH</em>). The memorial stone is the narrative's theological capstone: the victory is concretized in a named monument that encodes the lesson — YHWH's help is the explanation of Israel's survival. Ironically, an earlier place had been called Ebenezer — the site of Israel's defeat at Aphek (4:1). Samuel names the new stone the same name, converting a place of shame into a place of help-memory.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Philistines were subdued and did not come again into the territory of Israel. The hand of YHWH was against the Philistines all the days of Samuel. The summary is literary idealization of Samuel's period — the Philistine threat does not actually disappear (they are active threats in Saul's reign, chs 13-14). But the meaning is that YHWH's hand, expressed through Samuel's intercession and covenant faithfulness, provided a period of relative stability. The contrast with the period before Samuel's reform is the point.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Cities from Ekron to Gath that the Philistines had taken from Israel were restored. The territorial recovery implies that the Aphek defeat had resulted in territorial losses beyond mere military casualties — Philistine garrisons had taken Israelite settlements. Samuel's period saw these recovered. There was also peace with the Amorites — the indigenous Canaanite population Israel had co-existed with uneasily throughout the judges period.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Samuel judged Israel all the days of his life. His circuit — Bethel, Gilgal, Mizpah, returning to Ramah — was the administrative geography of the central highlands: a judge's circuit court covering the major population centers of Benjamin, southern Ephraim, and the Shephelah approaches. The circuit is approximately a 60-70 km loop through the hill country. Samuel is simultaneously prophet, priest, and judge — the last person to hold all three offices simultaneously in Israel.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The annual circuit covered Bethel (a major sanctuary since the patriarchal period), Gilgal (the Conquest covenant-renewal site), and Mizpah (the assembly and judicial center). Each site carried distinct traditions: Bethel was associated with Jacob's ladder vision, Gilgal with the first Passover in the land, Mizpah with covenant warfare. Samuel's circuit integrates all the major covenant-memory sites into a single judicial administration.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ramah was Samuel's home and the site of an altar he built to YHWH. The home-altar is appropriate for a prophetic figure: Samuel's household worship is the pattern of his life. Ramah is identified with er-Ram, approximately 8 km north of Jerusalem, in Benjaminite territory. The altar Samuel builds at Ramah is the priestly complement to his prophetic activity — he is not merely a spokesperson but a sacrificing mediator.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>When Samuel grew old he appointed his sons as judges over Israel — Joel in Beersheba and Abijah in the south. The geographical posting to Beersheba, the southernmost major city of Judah, is notable: Samuel's sons are stationed far from Ramah, perhaps to extend judicial coverage to the periphery. The appointment of sons to succeed raises the specter of the Eli pattern: Eli's sons corrupted the Shiloh priesthood (2:12-17); now Samuel's sons corrupt the southern judiciary. The parallel is the narrator's structural comment on institutional succession.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Joel and Abijah serve as judges at Beersheba. Joel means 'YHWH is God' and Abijah means 'my father is YHWH' — both names encode the covenant theology that their conduct will contradict. The irony of names meaning 'YHWH is God' and 'YHWH is my father' being given to men who perverted justice is the type of bitter wordplay the Deuteronomistic historian deploys throughout.</p>",
    "3": "<p>His sons did not walk in his ways but turned after dishonest gain (<em>wayṭû ʾaḥărê haṯṯāʿ</em>) — the word <em>beṣaʿ</em> (dishonest gain/unjust profit) appears in Exodus 18:21 as the negative quality Moses's judges must not have. Joel and Abijah took bribes and perverted justice. The perversion of justice by judicial officials was the central social-legal failure that the prophets would condemn throughout the monarchic period (Amos 5:12; Mic 3:11; Isa 1:23).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The elders of Israel gather and come to Samuel at Ramah. They constitute themselves as a formal delegation — this is a covenant assembly of representatives bringing a covenant complaint. The gathering at Ramah replicates the judicial geography of Samuel's circuit: they come to the judge's home city to address the judge directly. The complaint is legitimate: the judicial system Samuel established is failing at the succession level.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Behold, you are old and your sons do not walk in your ways. Now appoint for us a king to judge us like all the nations (<em>kəḵol-haggôyim</em>).' The three-part rationale — Samuel's age, sons' failure, comparison to the nations — is a formal constitutional petition. 'Like all the nations' is the theologically loaded phrase: Israel was constituted as explicitly not like the nations (Exod 19:5-6, 'a kingdom of priests and a holy nation'). The request to be like the nations is a self-conscious rejection of Israel's covenant distinctiveness.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The thing displeased Samuel when they said 'Give us a king to judge us,' and Samuel prayed to YHWH. Samuel's displeasure is personal — he interprets the request as a rejection of his own leadership. YHWH immediately corrects this reading (v7): the rejection is not of Samuel but of YHWH. Samuel's initial displeasure, honestly recorded, shows that YHWH's prophets were not dispassionate instruments but real people with personal investments in their ministry.</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH says to Samuel: 'Obey the voice of the people in all that they say to you, for they have not rejected you, but they have rejected me from being king over them.' YHWH's self-interpretation of Israel's request is the theological center of the chapter — and of the entire monarchy theology. The request for a human king is, at its root, a rejection of theocratic governance. YHWH is still the true king; the human king will be a concession to human weakness, not a superior arrangement.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'According to all the deeds that they have done, from the day I brought them up from Egypt even to this day, forsaking me and serving other gods, so they are also doing to you.' YHWH places the demand for a king in the long history of Israelite apostasy: the Exodus → idolatry → judges cycle has been Israel's constant pattern. The monarchy is not a new departure but another iteration of the same basic rejection of YHWH's authority. The form changes; the problem is the same.</p>",
    "9": "<p>YHWH instructs Samuel to obey them but to 'solemnly warn them and show them the ways of the king who shall reign over them' (<em>wəhāgêḏ tāgîḏ lāhem mišpaṭ hammelek ʾăšer yimlōḵ ʿălêhem</em>). The phrase <em>mišpaṭ hammelek</em> — the 'manner/right/custom of the king' — describes the royal extraction system. Samuel is to make the political economy of monarchy visible before the people consent to it. The warning is educational disclosure, not merely complaint.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Samuel tells the people who are asking for a king all the words of YHWH. The speech that follows (vv11-18) is the most detailed description of royal administrative practice in the Hebrew Bible — and it accurately describes the administrative apparatus of a Near Eastern monarchy as evidenced from Ugarit, Egypt, and Mesopotamia.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'This will be the behavior of the king who will reign over you: He will take your sons and appoint them to his chariots and to be his horsemen.' Chariot forces required specialized training and maintenance; royal chariot corps drew from the population by conscription. Israelite society had no standing chariot force — the demand for a king who 'fights our battles' (v20) implicitly required one. The taking of sons for military service is the first and most personally felt form of royal extraction.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The king will appoint commanders of thousands and commanders of fifties — a decimal military administrative structure consistent with both Israelite tribal organization and broader ANE armies. He will set some to plow and reap his ground — royal estates requiring labor levies — and to make weapons and equipment for his chariots. The combination of military and agricultural labor conscription was standard in both Egypt and Syria-Palestine for monarchic economies.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'He will take your daughters to be perfumers and cooks and bakers.' Royal households required skilled domestic labor — perfumery (for cosmetics, anointing oils, and cultic use), cooking, and baking at a scale impossible for individual households. The Egyptian royal household records from the New Kingdom period list exactly these categories of female palace workers. Samuel's warning is not hypothetical; it describes what Israel could observe in Egyptian and Canaanite court economies.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'He will take the best of your fields and vineyards and olive orchards and give them to his servants.' Royal land redistribution to courtiers and military officials was the economic engine of ANE monarchy — Ugaritic land grants to royal officials are extensively documented in the excavated archives. The taking of agricultural land was existentially threatening in a subsistence-farming economy where family land was both livelihood and inheritance.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'He will take a tenth of your grain and your vineyards and give it to his officers and to his servants.' The ten-percent royal tithe is the tax structure documented in the Ugaritic economic texts and consistent with Egyptian administrative records. The irony is pointed: YHWH had required a tithe (Num 18:21-24; Deut 14:22-29) for the support of Levites and the poor; the king will require a parallel tithe for the support of his court apparatus.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'He will take your male servants and female servants and the best of your young men and your donkeys and put them to his work.' The comprehensive extraction — human, animal, and agricultural labor — describes the corvée system (forced labor on royal projects) documented across the ancient Near East. Solomon's later use of corvée (1 Kings 5:13-18) and Rehoboam's threat to intensify it (1 Kings 12:4-14) are the historical fulfillments of this warning.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'He will take a tenth of your flocks, and you shall be his slaves.' The closing intensification — from taking (vv11-16) to slave status — represents the endpoint of the royal extraction logic: a population sufficiently diminished by taxes, conscription, and land-seizure becomes functionally enslaved to the royal economy regardless of formal status. The word <em>ʿăḇāḏîm</em> (slaves/servants) is the term Israel used to describe their condition in Egypt.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And in that day you will cry out because of your king, whom you have chosen for yourselves, but YHWH will not answer you in that day.' The warning's culmination is that the very mechanism they are choosing — a king to 'fight our battles' — will produce the same kind of oppression that prompted Israel's original cry in Egypt. And unlike the Exodus, YHWH will not respond to this cry: they chose this, and the consequences are theirs to bear. The circular logic — from Egypt's slavery → Exodus → monarchy → new slavery — is the Deuteronomistic History's meta-narrative of Israel's freedom squandered.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The people refuse to listen to Samuel's voice: 'No! But there shall be a king over us.' The blunt refusal — <em>lōʾ</em>, no — followed by insistence is the covenant rejection in its baldest form. Samuel has delivered YHWH's word, described the consequences, and warned explicitly. The people have heard and chosen anyway. This is not ignorance but informed rejection.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'That we also may be like all the nations, and that our king may judge us and go out before us and fight our battles.' The three functions of the desired king — judicial, military leadership, battle leadership — are all functions YHWH had been performing through judges and prophets. The explicit desire to 'be like all the nations' repeats the phrase of v5 and confirms the theological character of the request: Israel is choosing assimilation over covenant distinctiveness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Samuel hears all the people's words and repeats them in the ears of YHWH. The act of speaking the people's request back to YHWH is intercession as reporting — Samuel presents the people's will to the divine king for final decision. YHWH has already decided (v7-9) but Samuel still acts as the proper mediatorial channel between the people and their sovereign.</p>",
    "22": "<p>YHWH says: 'Obey their voice and make them a king.' Samuel then dismisses the people to their own cities. YHWH's final word is concession without endorsement: 'make them a king' is compliance with their request, not approval of it. The concession theology — YHWH giving what is asked while warning of consequences — is the theological posture of a covenant partner who respects human freedom even when that freedom is used destructively. Samuel's dismissal sends the people home; the next chapter will show YHWH's specific choice of whom to anoint.</p>"
  }
}

